                <head>224. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>In telegram 163603 to San José, June 24, the Department instructed <persName
                        corresp="#p_WM_1">Weissman</persName> to contact <persName corresp="#p_CA_1"
                        >Calero</persName> and “as many of <gloss target="#t_FAO_1">FAO</gloss>
                    leaders as possible” to “explain new opportunities” provided by the Meeting of
                    Foreign Ministers of the Organization of American States (<gloss
                        target="#t_MFM_1">MFM</gloss>) resolution “for renewed effort to persuade
                        <persName corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName> to step down and clear the
                    way for new dialogue on establishment of Government of National Reconciliation.”
                    (National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign
                    Policy File, P840133–1562) <persName corresp="#p_CA_1">Calero</persName>’s
                    response, as given in telegram 2685 from San José, June 25, indicated “no clear
                    strategy” to “take advantage of opportunity created by <gloss target="#t_MFM_1"
                        >MFM</gloss> resolution;” and his belief that conditions were “sufficient
                    for direct negotiation between <persName corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName>
                    and <gloss target="#t_USG_1">USG</gloss>.” (Carter Library, Donated Material,
                    Papers of <persName corresp="#p_MWF_1">Walter F. Mondale</persName>, Box 63,
                    Foreign Countries—Nicaragua, 1977–1980)</p>
                <p>In telegram 163604 to Managua, June 24, the Department instructed <persName
                        corresp="#p_TFMJ_1">Tucker</persName> to contact <persName
                        corresp="#p_RRC_1">Cordova Rivas</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_CJ_4"
                        >Jaime Chamorro</persName>, and other Broad Opposition Front (<gloss
                        target="#t_FAO_1">FAO</gloss>) leaders with the same message given to
                        <persName corresp="#p_CA_1">Calero</persName>. (National Archives, <gloss
                        target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign Policy File, P850036–1777)
                        <gloss target="#t_FAO_1">FAO</gloss> leaders met at the Embassy in Managua
                    to discuss their response to the <gloss target="#t_MFM_1">MFM</gloss> resolution
                    and their independence from the Sandinista National Liberation Front. (Telegram
                    2787 from Managua, June 24, National Archives, <gloss target="#t_RG_1"
                        >RG</gloss> 59, Central Foreign Policy File, P850036–1781) Telegram 2793
                    from Managua, June 24, included an informal translation of the <gloss
                        target="#t_FAO_1">FAO</gloss> declaration in response to the <gloss
                        target="#t_MFM_1">MFM</gloss> resolution, which endorsed <persName
                        corresp="#p_SDA_1">Somoza</persName>’s departure and sought to ensure
                    sufficient political breadth in the “Junta of the Government of National
                    Reconstruction” to achieve the “democratic and pluralist objectives which the
                    country needs.” (Carter Library, National Security Affairs, Staff Material,
                    North/South, Pastor Files, Country Files, Box 35, Nicaragua: 6/21–24/79)</p>
